---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About | Stitch & Spec"
  description="Stitch & Spec is an independent research publication that maps sewing and embroidery buyer questions to machine specifications, manufacturer documentation, and retailer data."
>
  <article class="trust-page">
    <header class="trust-hero">
      <p class="publication-kicker">Independent research publication</p>
      <h1>About Stitch &amp; Spec</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Stitch &amp; Spec maps buyer questions to machine specifications, manufacturer documentation, and retailer data so sewing and embroidery buyers can make decisions around their actual projects — not brand hype.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="trust-panel mission-panel" aria-labelledby="mission-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="section-label">Mission</p>
        <h2 id="mission-heading">Decision support before product persuasion.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Our mission is to make machine research easier to trust. Instead of treating every buyer as if they need the same “best” machine, Stitch &amp; Spec starts with the decision a reader is actually trying to make: hoop size, fabric handling, service access, upgrade risk, workflow speed, or project fit.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is a practical research path: define the project, identify the relevant specifications, compare the tradeoffs, and move to the next question with less uncertainty.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="method-grid" aria-labelledby="method-heading">
      <div class="method-intro">
        <p class="section-label">Editorial methodology</p>
        <h2 id="method-heading">How the research is built</h2>
        <p>
          Stitch &amp; Spec is not an expert opinion blog. It is an independent editorial resource that organizes public source material into buyer decision frameworks.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="method-list">
        <div class="method-step">
          <h3>Start with the buyer question</h3>
          <p>Each page begins with the decision someone is trying to make, such as whether a 4×4 embroidery hoop is enough, whether a domestic machine can handle denim, or when a serger is the better tool.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-step">
          <h3>Translate specs into practical tradeoffs</h3>
          <p>Manufacturer documentation and retailer specifications are used to connect features to real constraints: hoop area, throat space, presser-foot control, stitch options, speed, weight, accessories, and service access.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="method-step">
          <h3>Structure the answer neutrally</h3>
          <p>Recommendations are organized around fit, limits, and avoid-if conditions so readers can see why one machine category may work for a project while another may create friction.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="trust-panel team-panel" aria-labelledby="team-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="section-label">Published by</p>
        <h2 id="team-heading">The Stitch &amp; Spec Editorial Team</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        The Stitch &amp; Spec Editorial Team builds buyer decision frameworks from neutral sourcing, manufacturer documentation, retailer specifications, and clearly structured comparison criteria. The team’s editorial commitment is to separate practical machine-fit questions from brand messaging, keep research source-backed, and make tradeoffs visible before a reader clicks through to a retailer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="trust-panel affiliate-note" aria-labelledby="affiliate-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="section-label">Affiliate transparency</p>
        <h2 id="affiliate-heading">Commissions do not determine editorial recommendations.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Stitch &amp; Spec may earn commissions through affiliate relationships when readers click qualifying retailer links. Those relationships never influence editorial conclusions, page structure, or which tradeoffs are shown. Affiliate links help support the publication, but recommendations remain based on project fit, specifications, source material, and buyer decision context.
      </p>
      <p><a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">Read the affiliate disclosure</a> or <a href="/editorial-policy/">review the editorial policy</a>.</p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
